From: SeongJae Park <sj@kernel.org>
Date: Tue, 10 Feb 2026 21:45:16 -0800
Subject: [PATCH] ==== reclaim,lru_sort: monitor all system rams ====

mm/damon/reclaim,lru_sort: monitor all system rams by default

DAMON_RECLAIM and DAMON_LRU_SORT set the biggest 'System RAM' resource
of the system as the default monitoring target address range.  The
intent behind the design is for minimizing the monitoring overhead by
default.  Of course this can result in an odd setup when there are
multiple discrete System RAMs of considerable sizes.  For example, there
are 500 GiB of System RAM, 500 GiB of System RAM, and 10 MiB of
non-System RAM between those, only the first 500 GiB will be set as the
monitoring region by default.  This is particularly common on NUMA
systems.  But users can set the monitoring target address range using
the module prameters if that doesn't work for them.  In other words, the
design trades the ease of the setup for the monitoring overhead
reduction.

However, because DAMON utilizes the sampling based access check and the
adaptive regions adjustment mechanisms, the reduction of the overhead is
negligible in most setups.  Meanwhile, the setup complexity is causing
real headaches for users who need to run those on various types of
systems.

Set the phyiscal address range that can cover all System RAM areas of
the system as the default monitoring regions for all (non-sample) DAMON
modules.

Note that the old behavior is documented for DAMON_RECLAIM and
DAMON_LRU_SORT.  So technically speaking, this is changing the
documented behavior.  However, it makes no sense to believe there is a
real use case that really depend on the old weird behavior.  Just change
the behavior and update the document.

Signed-off-by: SeongJae Park <sj@kernel.org>
